Data Wrangling

  • Often you have many tables of data and need to combine them to answer a question
  • Multiple tables of data are called relational data because we are interested in the relations rather than the individual data sets

nycflights13 Data

Relational data

Need verbs that work with pairs of tables. There are 3 families of verbs:

  • Mutating joins - add new variables to one data frame from matching observations in another
  • Filtering joins - filter observations from one data frame based on whether or not they match an observation in the other table
  • Set operations - treat observations as if they were set elements

Toy example

band <- tribble(
   ~name,   ~band,  
  "Mick", "Stones",
  "John", "Beetles",
  "Paul", "Beetles"
)

instrument <- tribble(
  ~name, ~plays,
  "John", "guitar",
  "Paul", "bass",
  "Keith", "guitar"
)

Toy example

Join

left_join(band,instrument, by ="name")
## # A tibble: 3  3
##   name  band    plays 
##   <chr> <chr>   <chr> 
## 1 Mick  Stones  <NA>  
## 2 John  Beetles guitar
## 3 Paul  Beetles bass
right_join(band,instrument, by ="name")
## # A tibble: 3  3
##   name  band    plays 
##   <chr> <chr>   <chr> 
## 1 John  Beetles guitar
## 2 Paul  Beetles bass  
## 3 Keith <NA>    guitar

inner_join(band,instrument, by ="name")
## # A tibble: 2  3
##   name  band    plays 
##   <chr> <chr>   <chr> 
## 1 John  Beetles guitar
## 2 Paul  Beetles bass
full_join(band,instrument, by ="name")
## # A tibble: 4  3
##   name  band    plays 
##   <chr> <chr>   <chr> 
## 1 Mick  Stones  <NA>  
## 2 John  Beetles guitar
## 3 Paul  Beetles bass  
## 4 Keith <NA>    guitar

gather()

cases <- tribble(
  ~country, ~"2011", ~"2012",~"2013",
  "FR",  7000, 6900, 7000,
  "DE",  5800, 6000, 6200,

spread()

pollution <- tribble(
  ~city,   ~size, ~amount, 
  "New York", "large",     23,
  "New York", "small",     14,
  "London", "large",       22,
  "London", "small",       16,

who data

The data contain tuberculosis (TB) cases broken down by year, country, age, gender, and diagnosis method from the 2014 World Health Organization Global Tuberculosis Report

-   `country`, `iso2`, `iso3` - country identifiers
-   `year` - year
-   other columns names - encode type of TB case, sex, and age

Your turn

names(who) <- str_replace(names(who), "newrel", "new_rel")

  • Gather the 5th through 60th columns of who into a pair of key:value columns named codes and n.Then select just the country, year, codes and n variables.

separate()

who %>% gather(codes,n, 5:60) %>%

Your turn

  • Separate the sexage column into sex and age columns.

unite()

Unites columns into single column by combining cells.

unite()

who %>%
  gather("codes", "n", 5:60) %>%
  select(-iso2, -iso3) %>%
  separate(codes, c("new", "type", "sexage"), sep = "_") %>%
  select(-new) %>%
  separate(sexage, into = c("sex", "age"), sep = 1,convert=TRUE) %>%
  unite("sexage2", sex, age, sep = "-")
## # A tibble: 405,440  5
